  'rainy-day-banff': `
<p>Even in the mountains, rain happens. But a rainy day in Banff doesn't have to mean a wasted day. From world-class museums to cozy cafes, hot springs to bowling alleys, there are plenty of ways to enjoy Banff when the weather turns. Here are the best indoor activities and rainy day ideas.</p>

<h2>Hot Springs & Spas</h2>

<h3>Banff Upper Hot Springs</h3>
<p>Rain makes the hot springs even better. Soak in naturally heated mineral water (37-40°C) while rain patters around you and clouds swirl through the mountains above. It's atmospheric, relaxing, and you're getting wet anyway. Open daily year-round, adults $9.25.</p>

<h3>Fairmont Willow Stream Spa</h3>
<p>Treat yourself to a full spa day at the Fairmont Banff Springs. The Willow Stream Spa features an indoor mineral pool, waterfall, steam rooms, and an extensive menu of massages and treatments. Day access from $75.</p>

<h3>Kananaskis Nordic Spa</h3>
<p>Worth the 1-hour drive. The Nordic-inspired hydrotherapy circuit of hot pools, cold plunges, steam rooms, and saunas is designed to be enjoyed in any weather. Some say rain and mist make the outdoor pools even more magical. Book ahead — from $90.</p>

<h2>Museums & Cultural Sites</h2>

<h3>Whyte Museum of the Canadian Rockies</h3>
<p>Banff's premier museum tells the story of human life in the Canadian Rockies through art, photography, and artifacts. Rotating exhibits showcase mountain culture, Indigenous history, and contemporary art. A thoughtful way to spend 2-3 hours.</p>

<h3>Cave and Basin National Historic Site</h3>
<p>The birthplace of Canada's national park system. In 1883, three railway workers discovered natural hot springs in a cave here, leading to the creation of Banff National Park in 1885. Interactive exhibits, a restored cave, and the Discovery Walk make this a fascinating rainy-day visit.</p>

<h3>Banff Park Museum</h3>
<p>Canada's oldest natural history museum (opened 1903) housed in a beautiful log building on Banff Avenue. Taxidermy displays and exhibits on Rocky Mountain wildlife are surprisingly engaging. A National Historic Site and a quiet gem.</p>

<h2>Food & Drink Experiences</h2>

<h3>Park Distillery</h3>
<p>Tour a craft distillery that uses glacial water to make its spirits, then settle in for campfire-cooked food and creative cocktails. The cozy, dimly lit atmosphere is perfect for a rainy afternoon or evening.</p>

<h3>Wild Flour Bakery</h3>
<p>Grab a window seat with a sourdough croissant and coffee, and watch the rain fall on Banff Avenue. Their baked goods are some of the best in town.</p>

<h3>Banff Ave Brewing Co.</h3>
<p>Banff's original craft brewery. Sample a flight of house-brewed beers paired with solid pub food. The rooftop patio has a covered section if the rain eases up.</p>

<h2>Fun & Entertainment</h2>

<h3>High Rollers</h3>
<p>A bowling alley meets cocktail lounge on Banff Avenue. Roll a few frames while sipping craft cocktails — it's fun for couples, families, and groups alike. A great way to kill a few hours.</p>

<h3>Lux Cinema</h3>
<p>Catch a movie at the Lux Cinema in the heart of Banff. It's a small, charming theatre with new releases and a full concession stand.</p>

<h3>Shopping on Banff Avenue</h3>
<p>Browse the shops along Banff Avenue for outdoor gear, Canadian souvenirs, Indigenous art, and local crafts. The <strong>Banff Indian Trading Post</strong> has authentic Indigenous art and artifacts. Many shops have covered entries, making browsing pleasant even in rain.</p>

<h2>Low-Cloud Adventures</h2>
<p>If you don't mind getting a little wet, some activities are actually enhanced by moody weather:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Johnston Canyon:</strong> The canyon waterfalls are even more dramatic in the rain, and the covered catwalks provide some shelter</li>
<li><strong>Fenland Trail:</strong> A short forest loop where the tree canopy provides natural rain cover and the wet forest smells incredible</li>
<li><strong>Bow Falls:</strong> A quick walk from town — waterfalls in the rain are extra powerful</li>
<li><strong>Drive the Bow Valley Parkway:</strong> Wildlife is often more active in overcast, rainy conditions. Stay dry in your car while watching for bears and elk</li>
</ul>

<div class="tip-box"><strong>Silver Lining:</strong> Many of Banff's most dramatic photographs are taken in moody, overcast weather. Clouds and mist clinging to mountain peaks create an atmosphere that bluebird days can't match. Bring your camera.</div>
